## TinaCMS And Global Visual Editing

If by globally and visually you mean changing site-wide colors, fonts, spacing, and component variants across all pages from one place without touching code, TinaCMS does not do that out of the box. TinaCMS is fundamentally content-first.

It can edit content blocks inline or through the sidebar per page or per component, but it does not automatically propagate design-token changes globally unless you wire those values to a shared config.

## Core Limitations To Know

1) TinaCMS can edit content fields quickly and safely.
2) It cannot magically rewrite global Tailwind tokens or CSS scales.
3) Global colors, typography scales, spacing scales, and style tokens usually live in code.
4) To make those values editable, you define explicit fields and make components consume those fields.

## Workaround: Centralized Theme JSON

A practical approach is a centralized theme file that stores editable tokens. Example:

{
  "colors": {
    "primary": "#1e90ff",
    "secondary": "#ff6347",
    "background": "#ffffff",
    "text": "#000000"
  },
  "spacing": {
    "small": "8px",
    "medium": "16px",
    "large": "32px"
  },
  "typography": {
    "fontFamily": "Arial, sans-serif",
    "headingSize": "2rem",
    "bodySize": "1rem"
  },
  "buttons": {
    "variant": "rounded"
  }
}

Store this file in your content backend and treat it as a source of truth for global theme values.

## Expose Theme Fields In TinaCMS

Then expose those keys in Tina so editors can update them visually. Example form setup:

import { useCMS, useForm, usePlugin } from "tinacms"
import themeData from "./theme.json"

const formConfig = {
  id: "global-theme",
  label: "Global Theme",
  initialValues: themeData,
  fields: [
    { name: "colors.primary", label: "Primary Color", component: "color" },
    { name: "colors.secondary", label: "Secondary Color", component: "color" },
    { name: "spacing.medium", label: "Medium Spacing", component: "text" },
    { name: "typography.fontFamily", label: "Font Family", component: "text" },
    {
      name: "buttons.variant",
      label: "Button Style",
      component: "select",
      options: ["rounded", "square"]
    }
  ],
  onSubmit: (values) => {
    // persist theme values to your source of truth
  }
}

const [themeForm] = useForm(formConfig)
usePlugin(themeForm)

## Make Components Consume Global Tokens

Theme edits become global only when components read from that shared config. Example:

import theme from "./theme.json"

export function Button({ children }) {
  return (
    <button
      style={{
        backgroundColor: theme.colors.primary,
        color: theme.colors.text,
        padding: theme.spacing.medium,
        borderRadius: theme.buttons.variant === "rounded" ? "9999px" : "4px",
        fontFamily: theme.typography.fontFamily
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  )
}

You can apply the same pattern to layout variants (for example grid vs list) and a ThemeProvider for optional live preview while editing.

## Summary And Takeaway

Out of the box: inline text and media editing is strong, and page-level component visibility is manageable.

Not out of the box: full site-wide visual design-system control.

Workaround: create a global theme/config document, expose it in Tina, and ensure every relevant component consumes those values.

Takeaway: TinaCMS can support global visual editing effectively, but only after you explicitly model and wire design tokens. It will not infer your design system automatically.
